Weight Factoring¶

In addition to the data preparation (see last post), applying weights is necessary for a more accurate calculation. The weight factor: $ \sqrt{c_p \rho \Delta d_{i,i-1} \cos{\phi}\Delta \theta \Delta \phi }$ is applied to factor 2 main properties: physical space and materialistic properties,.¶

The physical space factoring can easily be explained by thinking of each gridbox as a rectangular prism. The volume of a rectangular prism is $ V = Bh$ (base area x height). Base area is $ \Delta \theta \Delta \phi$ and the height is the thickness, or $\Delta d_{i,i-1} = distance_i - distance_{i-1}$. The $\cos \phi$ is to account for the spherical nature of the Earth because the Earth bulges near the equator and converges near the poles.¶

The materialistic properties are to account for the differing properties of air and water. Density even varies within air. A gridbox of air in a high altitude would have less air then a gridbox of air near sea level, despite having the same volume. Likewise, heat capacity is taken into account for the difference in the transfer of heat between water and air.¶

Weight Calculations¶

Some additional side calculations will be needed for the weight factoring. For example, in the NOAA air dataset, the levels are given in terms of pressure (hPa) instead of altitude (m). To do this, this variation of the ideal gas law $P = P_0 e^{\frac{-gM(h-h_0}{RT}}$ is used. Some assumptions will have to be made: air pressure at sea level is consistently 1013.25 mbar and (due to varying temperature), $T = climatology$ in Kelvin. Other information not given are the densities of each layer. For water, all layers are assumed to be $1000 \frac{kg}{m^3}$ whereas for air, the equation: $ \rho = \frac{P}{2.869T}$ with $T =climatology$ in Kelvin again.¶

Constants needed are:¶

$$g = 9.8, M = 0.0289644, r = 8.31432, c_{pair} = 1.005, c_{pwater} = 4.812 $$

Now the weighted anomalies can be calculated show below:¶

vweightedanom = stnd_anom * weightFactor
